               <p>784. <persName id="def1-784-18771022" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-784-18771022" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-784-18771022" type="age" value="37"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-784-18771022" type="surname" value="SINCLAIR"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-784-18771022" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">JAMES SINCLAIR</hi> (37)</persName>, <persName id="def2-784-18771022" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def2-784-18771022" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def2-784-18771022" type="age" value="28"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def2-784-18771022" type="surname" value="RYAN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def2-784-18771022" type="given" value="GEORGE"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">GEORGE RYAN</hi> (28)</persName>, <hi rend="italic">and</hi> 
                  <persName id="def3-784-18771022" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def3-784-18771022" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def3-784-18771022" type="age" value="49"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def3-784-18771022" type="surname" value="BLED"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def3-784-18771022" type="given" value="ISAAC"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">ISAAC BLED</hi> (49)</persName>
                  <rs id="t18771022-784-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18771022-784-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18771022-784-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="stealingFromMaster"></interp>, Stealing eight bales of wool of the <persName id="t18771022-name-225" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-225" type="gender" value="indeterminate"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18771022-784-offence-1 t18771022-name-225"></join>London and St. Katharine's Dock Company</persName>, the masters of Sinclair and Ryan.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. GREEN</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18771022-name-226" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-226" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-226" type="surname" value="YOUNG"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-226" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN YOUNG</persName>
                  </hi>. I live at Globe Street, and am in the Company's service—it is my duty to lock up the crescent warehouse at sis at night and unlock it at sis in the morning—none of the men have any right to stop there during the night—before locking up I call "All out"—On the 28th September, when I unlocked at sis o'clock in the morning, I saw Bird, who is an extra labourer—I went straight up to him and asked</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="187710220053"></xptr>
               <p>"How came you here? Were you drunk? Did you get locked in by accident?"—he said "Oh no, nothing of the sort"—I said "Where did you sleep?"—he said "That is nothing to do with you, you need not trouble yourself about that, I am not alone; we have a man named Jimmy here"—Jimmy is Sinclair—I—went with him and saw Sinclair in what we call the big room—he was sewing up a bale—I said "Hallo Jim, what do you do here? locked yourself up so that the rats don't get in while you are asleep?"—he said "We have got a job on, and we are doing it, it is nothing to do with you"—I left them, but shortly afterwards saw them again, when Bird said "Look here, you run no risk in anything of this sort; if you want anything in the shape of money you can have it"—I said "I do not under<lb></lb>stand it"—I think they said I could have 10<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. at once if I liked—I said "No, no; nothing of that sort"—I did not see Ryan at all daring that time—at their request I had some gin-and-milk with them, and then we separated for breakfast—when they came in again I said "Look here, what were you doing of?"—they said "Well now, it is nothing at all to do with you, we have got a job to do; you run no risk, we have got to make up some bales to bring in, and they will be called land carriages: the bales will be brought in, the order will be brought back again from the City, and the order received in the regular way, the bales weighed, brought forward when, required, and there it is; it will pay us well to do so, and if you want a sovereign you can have it"—I informed Mr. Hunt at ten minutes to eight.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18771022-name-227" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-227" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-227" type="surname" value="GRIGG"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-227" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>THOMAS GRIGG</persName>
                  </hi>. I am superintendent of the Dock Company's Police—on 28th September I received information and sent for Sinclair and Bird, and saw them separately—I said to-Sinclair "I learn you were at our warehouse last night," and told him it was a serious matter, and cautioned him—he said "It was arranged with foreman Ryan about a month ago that I, Bird, and another man by the name of Carr should be in the warehouse and make up some bales of wool; I and Carr remained in one night, about the 13th, and made up two bales: on the following night we stopped in again and made up two more, making in all four bales, which on the following day were put into the scale; Ryan told us to mark them A. M. and a diamond No. I to 4, which was done"—Sinclair then said he had received about 30<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. for that transaction, and afterwards received a few shillings at the time, about 10<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. more—he said "Nothing more transpired until the previous day, when Ryan came to Sinclair and said 'You had better stop in again to-night with Bird and Carr and make up four bales more, get them marked A. M. diamond No. 5 to 8,' which we did; the bags were brought to the scale and there they remain ready to be—weighed"—I asked Bird what he had to say, and he said he knew nothing about the wool whatever; that he was working in the wool warehouse on the previous day, and that having left his jacket in the foreman's box he went there to get it, and on his return he found the door locked, and rather than make any bother in reference to his being locked in, he remained there all night; but he admitted having seen Sinclair there about five o'clock in the morning—I afterwards brought them to<lb></lb>gether, and read each other's statements so that they knew what each had said—I then sent for Ryan, and told him what Sinclair had said—Ryan said "It is no good denying facts, it is true; I have done it to make too ends meet"—I said "It is a very serious matter, and whatever you</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="187710220054"></xptr>
               <p>have to say may be made use of as evidence"—he said "I cannot help it; I may as well say it, and make a clean breast of it"—he said a person of the name of Hammond, about two months ago, asked him to get some bales of wool, and about the 13th September he prepared four bales, got them to the sale, passed them through the sale, and received 27<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. as the produce, which he divided between himself, Sinclair, Bird, and Carr—I showed Evan the order (<hi rend="italic">produced</hi>) A. M. I to 4, and asked him if he knew anything about it—he said "Yes, I received it from Mr. Hammond and have acted upon it"—he then said he saw Mr. Hammond on the 27th, and arranged to get four bales more—the four bales were marked "A. M. diamond 5 to 8," and they were placed ready for the scale, where I afterwards found them—I then called Bird in the presence of Ryan, and told him that Ryan had said it was arranged for him to re<lb></lb>main in with other men, and Ryan said "No good to be downhearted; tell the truth"—Bird said "Well, it is no good to deny it; I did remain in for one night, about the 13th, and we made up two or three bales then: I remained in last night and we made up four bales more, and we marked them A. M. and a diamond; I do not know whether they went to the scales"—the prisoners had no right to make up those bales, and no right to be in the warehouse at all.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18771022-name-228" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-228" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-228" type="surname" value="SLOCOMB"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-228" type="given" value="RICHARD HENRY"></interp>RICHARD HENRY SLOCOMB</persName>
                  </hi>. I am clerk to Mr. Mellor, who is clerk to the Great Eastern Railway Company—I wrote the order produced marked A—I received a copy from Mr. Hammond in. the presence of Mr. Mellor in the Wool Exchange, addressed to the superintendent of the London Docks—I copied it, and handed it back to Mr. Mellor—I went down to the docks daily during the sales—I saw Ryan and Hammond there—on the 14th September Hammond told me to ask Ryan to let him have the weights of the four bales—he did not say what four bales—I did not know what he meant—I told Ryan, and he said "I will see Mr. Ham<lb></lb>mond in Coleman Street."</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18771022-name-229" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-229" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-229" type="surname" value="MELLOR"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-229" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>JAMES MELLOR</persName>
                  </hi>. I am an officer of the Great Eastern Railway Com<lb></lb>pany, and acquainted with Mr. Hammond—previous to 12th September he came to me about writing some orders for him, giving me drafts of what he wanted written—I directed Mr. Slocomb to write that of the 15th—I think it is A. M. I to 4—the other I copied myself, and gave the copy to Hammond—I know Ryan as the foreman of the dock warehouse—I sent the documents on to Messrs. Jacomb and Co. at Hammond's direction, and afterwards received this cheque (<hi rend="italic">produced</hi>) for 56<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 9<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 1<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. from Messrs. Jacomb after the sale on loth September, and paid it to Mr. Hammond—I endorsed it—it is made payable to me.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18771022-name-230" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-230" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-230" type="surname" value="JACOMB"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-230" type="given" value="FREDERICK CHARLES"></interp>FREDERICK CHARLES JACOMB</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a wool-broker of the firm of Jacomb, Son, and Co., of 61, Moorgate Street—I received the order A. M. I to 4, and in consequence placed in my sale of loth September the four bales of wool—they <hi rend="italic">were</hi> lotted 17, and the sale effected on that day for 56<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 9<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 1<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.—I signed a delivery order for a number of bales, in which those four are included—the goods were delivered to my order from the Dock Com<lb></lb>pany—the cheque produced was given to Mr. Mellor by our firm—there are a great number of purchasers go to the docks when the bales are on show—every bale is shown—they pull out pieces of wool to examine it, and sometimes cut the bale right open and take out half the bale.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18771022-name-231" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-231" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-231" type="surname" value="WILLETT"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-231" type="given" value="FREDERICK"></interp>FREDERICK WILLETT</persName>
                  </hi>. I am cheque clerk to the Dock Company, and Ryan is foreman of the wool warehouse—Sinclair is a permanent</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="187710220055"></xptr>
               <p>labourer, and Bird is an extra labourer—on the 14th of September Evan gave me this order (<hi rend="italic">produced</hi>)—it was my duty to see the bales weighed and take the weights, and hand the orders up, for the weights to pass through the books of Company—Ryan simply told me to weigh the bales mentioned in the order, or see them weighed—if for land carriage the foreman would send them out—I saw a cart there—the other order (<hi rend="italic">produced</hi>) was also given me by Ryan, and the bales were brought up, and they were weighed in the regular course—none of the labourers have any right to stay there all night, or to touch any of the wool in the packing-room to make up into bales—the wool in the packing-room is used to fill up deficiencies—Ryan is warehouse foreman, not delivery foreman—it was his duty to receive goods coming by land carriage, and see them sent up to me to weigh.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18771022-name-232" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-232" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-232" type="surname" value="ROWAN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-232" type="given" value="ARCHIBALD"></interp>ARCHIBALD ROWAN</persName>
                  </hi>. I am delivery clerk to the Dock Company—I remember receiving this delivery order of Messrs. Jacomb and Co., and signed it clear for the delivery foreman to deliver by.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
